UNDIAGNOSED DIE-OFF, AVIAN - USA (TEXAS)
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 8 Jan 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: KeyTV.com [edited]
<http://keyetv.com/topstories/local_story_008221206.html>

Samples of 63 dead birds are in on their way to Texas Veterinary
Medical Diagnostic Laboratory in order to solve a mystery on Congress Ave.
Someone spotted a few of those dead grackles around 3 a.m. Monday and
called police.
The theory health experts are leaning toward is that this may be an
intentional poisoning. [It is not uncommon to find the avicide
Avitrol used in these types of cases, - Mod.TG]
Initially, police and firefighters called in all emergency responders
to rule out air contamination and terror attacks.
The hazardous material teams collected the bird from the streets,
sidewalks, and rooftops. Sixty-three dead birds, mostly grackles with
a few pigeons and sparrows in the mix.
Police shut down Congress Ave. from Cesar Chavez to 11th Street and
one block on either side until a little after noon. Health officials
immediately tested the air, called emergency rooms to check for
unusual illnesses that might be related, then tested the birds on site.
"The external feathers, based on some of the on site gas
chromatography testing that we did, were negative for any type of
volatile chemicals," said Dr. Adolfo Valadez, medical director for
Austin/Travis County Health and Human Services Department.
Health officials say this does not appear to be bird flu and it's the
wrong time of year for West Nile Virus. But nothing gets ruled out
until they get bacteria and virus tests back from Texas A&M and bird
flu test back from a lab in Ames, Iowa [The National Veterinary
Services Laboratory, NVSL].
"We may suspect a poisoning of those birds, but again I don't have
any confirmation of that, and, again, I still need final testing,"
Valadez said.
Experts say there is always the possibility of natural causes. They
say birds aren't the cleanest animals. They drink contaminated water
and spread disease quickly. The bottom line, health experts quickly
figured out there was no risk to public health and reopened the main
artery of downtown Austin.
Valadez says the tests they're waiting on will take days if not weeks.
Austin police say, if it turns out someone did poison these birds on
purpose, they could face criminal charges for violating health codes
or for unlicensed use of pesticides.
If you find suspicious dead birds, the health authority asks you call
311, so the city can compile that information.
[Byline: Kim Miller]
