Date: Fri, 12 Jan 2007 03:58:24 -0000
From: Bissett, James Stanley, Jr <jsb9338@neo.tamu.edu>

Subject: Undiagnosed avian die off
-----------------
In Austin, Texas, USA, there were over 60 avians (grackels, sparrows,
and pidgeons) found dead along Congress Ave. ERT [?emergency
response teams] teams and other health officials were there and had
collected the birds to send off for diagnostic testing. They do not
believe at this time that this is due to the avian influenza but that
of poisoning. There have been cases where poisoned grain had been
placed on the roofs of buildings in hopes of thinning out the bird
populations. There is no confirmatory results at this time.
--
James Bissett
Public Health Specialist
Texas Dept. of State Health Services
Public Health Headquarters,Region 7
<jsb9338@neo.tamu.edu>
[According to one article there were 63 birds, which in the face of
the perhaps thousands of grackles and pigeons is miniscule. It is not
uncommon for people to use Avitrol, an avian repellant, to try and
convince the birds to leave. The excitement of the bird colonies when
Avitrol is used sometimes results in some deaths. This would not be
uncommon. A discussion of Avitrol can be found on ProMED-mail post
20030215.0391.
Sources in Austin believe this was an excuse to exercise the hazmat
people, an opportunity for them to wear their suits without the
oppressive heat of Texas summers.
Weather reports indicate that the temperatures have had severe swings
but are seasonal for this time of year. Lows have been ranging to
approximately 30 degrees F while daytime temperatures may reach 60
degrees F. If the temperatures were more severe, it is possible that
it could be a case of cold shock. But I might expect more birds were
that the case.
With temperatures having such a wide swing, it is possible that the
birds, hungry in the early dawn and late evening, consumed some less
than wholesome material in the area and became sick from food
poisoning. More likely this would be called salmonellosis. Sick birds
can easily look drunk or have odd behavior.
It is the wrong time of year for birds to become intoxicated from
fermented berries, and literally die from the fermented berries, or
alcohol poisoning.
Cases like this have existed in Texas in the past and have been the
result of avitrol use or from salmonellosis.
Texas Veterinary Medical Diagnostic Laboratory and the National
Veterinary Services Laboratory will have results within a few days.
We look forward to an authoritative report from someone at the
laboratories. - Mod.TG]
